            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            
                            <p>A letter from H. G Brabazon, secretary of the Irish Professional Photographer's Association, to Robert Chalmers, under-secretary for Ireland (1856-1938). The letter concerns the damage to Dublin businesses due to the Rising. Brabazon states that the Irish Professional Photographer's Association have resolved to condemn the actions of the rebels and call on the government to fully compensate the men who have had property and business damaged. It goes on to state a copy of the resolution has been sent to Herbert Henry Asquith (1852-1928), David Lloyd George (1863-1945), Edward Carson (1854-1935) and John Redmond (1856-1918).</p>
                            
                        
                            
                        
                            
                            <p>Sir Robert Chalmers was sent to Ireland as replacement under-secretary for Sir Matthew Nathan, who had resigned along with Augustine Birrell, his chief secretary, following the outbreak of the Easter Rising in 1916.</p>
                            
                        
                    
                </note>
