<opener><address><addrLine>Hon Sec., H. G. BRABAZON,</addrLine>
<addrLine>16 HENRY STREETt.</addrLine>
<addrLine>Dublin,</address>

<dateline><date>May 26th. 1916.</date></dateline> 
<address>Sir Robert Chalmers,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Under Secretary for Ireland,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Dublin Castle,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Dublin.</addrLine></address>

<salute>Dear Sir,</salute></opener>
<p>At a special meeting held in the Gresham Hotel Dublin on the 
<lb/>night of the 25th, May, the following resolution was proposed and se-
<lb/>conded.</p>
<p>''That the members of the Irish Professional Photographers As-
<lb/>sociation condemn and deplore the recent regretable disturbance, and 
<lb/>we consider it the bounden duty of the Government to fully compensate 
<lb/>those whose property and business were destroyed, giving fullconsid-
<lb/>eration to the question of consequential damage, and we are of the
<lb/>opinion that it would be unjust to fix the amount of compensation on
<lb/>the basis of Insurance."</p>
<p>That copies of this resolution be sent to the Prime Minister
<lb/>The Right Hon. D. Lloyd George, Sir Robert Chalmers Under Secretary for
<lb/>Ireland, Sir Edward Carson M. P. Mr John Redmond M. P. the six Dublin
<lb/>members of Parliament, and Press.</p>

<closer><salute>I remain, Sir,
<lb/>Your most obedient servant,</salute>
<signed>Hon Sec.
<lb/>Henry G Brabazon</signed></closer>
        
    

    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        

         

